Training and Preparation

HYDERA ensures employees are trained on the safe handling of chemicals storage containers and how to respond appropriately, should a release occur.  Some examples of our preparation and training include:
	Written procedures to handle all types of emergencies;
	Regularly scheduled safety training for all personnel involved with covered chemical operations;
	Trained on-site emergency response teams; 
	Emergency planning sessions with the local fire department and county emergency personnel;
	Participation in annual county disaster drills;
	Routine testing of plant emergency response, alerting, and communications systems;
	Fully equipped emergency response vehicles; and 
	Certified Hazmat Team to respond to off-site transportation and distribution incidents.

VII. RELEASE PREVENTION AND CHEMICAL - SPECIFIC PREVENTION 

Assuring Safe Operations

HYDERA has established programs and activities to ensure safe operation of its systems.  Some examples include: 
	Personnel trained in the safe operations;
	Operating and maintenance procedures in place; 
	Hazard and operability studies conducted routinely; 
	Safety reviews conducted prior to making any changes to the operation or equipment;
	Health, environmental, and safety audits conducted to ensure compliance with regulations;
	Maintenance work planned ahead of time and work permits issued to assure work is done safely;
	Equipment, instruments, and piping regularly inspected to ensure integrity of the system; and
	All incidents investigated and action taken to prevent recurrence.

Designing for Safety

HYDERA has multiple safeguards and systems to reduce the likelihood of incidents, including:

	Equipment built to industry standards; 
	Instruments

provided to control the operation within safe limits;
	Emergency shutdown systems installed to immediately isolate the system and minimize upsets;
	Equipment located in enclosures or within equivalent secondary containment to reduce the effect of a release; 
	Gas detectors available to identify a possible release; and
	Relief devices installed to prevent overpressure of the system and safely discharge the material should an upset occur. 

VIII. IMPROVING SAFETY PROGRAM

HYDERA has a continuing commitment to improving safety performance in all areas of concern and will routinely review safe work practices, incidents, performance indicators, and operational procedures.
